On the night of June 5, 1864, I ran from Alice Grant in Wilmington, NC. She had bought me from merchant Horatio N. Gould of Alabama; he had been indicted a few years before for buying enslaved Africans illegally imported into the US on a ship named Wanderer. I was called MARY. https://t.co/VJ1Nqlfmv6
On this day in April 1854, I ran from the farm of Ann W. Walter on Maryland’s Eastern Shore. Her husband James had died recently and I took the opportunity to flee before she could sell me. I might have headed to DC or Baltimore, or to the North. My name was JOSHUA. https://t.co/MYE1bY8fu6
I ran but was caught in Lamar County, TX in November 1863, and held in the jail there at least through June 1864. Andrew J. Ward, fleeing ahead of Union troops, had taken some Arkansas leased convicts, including me, and a load of cotton through Texas. My name was BILL. https://t.co/aShpoc1ca1
I ran from Samuel W. Holden of Wilmington, NC in April 1864 when I was 14 years old; he had hired me from recently widowed Julia Fillyaw. She had also hired out men to the salt works on Middle Sound. I had friends and family in Wilmington who could harbor me. My name was NICEY. https://t.co/CwXATdj8ZD
I was jailed in Roxboro, NC in January 1856 on suspicion of being a runaway. I said I was from Greenville, VA, roughly 150 miles north of Roxboro. I was held in the Person County jail for a year, until January 1857. My name was WILLIAM MAYO. https://t.co/jzSLNjKMzz
I ran from the Wilmington, NC business of Adrian H. Van Bokkelen in the fall of 1855; I had been hired to him for the year of 1855 by Isaac Benners of New Bern. Benners would soon move to Alabama, and I might have wanted to stay near all my family in NC. My name was MACKLIN. https://t.co/pwdo4GSDbP
I ran from farmer Gideon E. Keen of Pittsylvania County, VA in August 1863, near the border of NC, and went to my family living near Bachelors Hall plantation in the same county. He was still looking for me in February 1864, but I was well hidden. My name was CLARA. https://t.co/zUKAiIey2g
I ran from barkeeper Patrick Gallager in May 1864, taking a pony and tack to speed my escape from Fort Bend County, Texas near Houston. Galveston had fallen back into Confederate hands in 1863, but I might have headed toward the coast to look for Union forces. I was called JACK. https://t.co/DURDgUJJMM
I ran from Michael Register’s farm on Moore’s Creek, 34 miles from Wilmington, NC; I left on the first of May, 1863, about the same time that Register died. I had hoped to seize the opportunity for escaping and getting paid for my work. https://t.co/FZAUC1s61d
I was taken to New Orleans city jail in August 1854; I told them I ran from either Mr. Crane of Missouri, or Mr. Talbot. I was still held there a month later, waiting to be taken back. I called myself WILSON. #blackhistory https://t.co/NDCwImRDy6
Several of us ran from the plantation of Samuel S. Simmons of Plymouth, NC on February 24th, 1856, possibly heading to Virginia or the Great Dismal Swamp to hide out.  Simmons was facing financial collapse and we would all be sold if we stayed. Our names were UNKNOWN. https://t.co/epsih2hACF
We ran from the Marion County, SC farm of Ezra M. Davis on Feb. 21, 1856.  The Wilmington & Manchester Railroad ran through nearby Florence, SC directly to the port of Wilmington, NC. Davis was still looking for us in March 1856. We were called JACK and BRIGHT. https://t.co/73V5OXcGpM
In July 1864, I slipped away into freedom in the city of Galveston, Texas. I had been bought by Captain Richard King, owner of the King Ranch, but he was running steamboats out of Mexico for the Confederate war effort and was not in Galveston. My name was CHARLES. https://t.co/E7PRpWcLD3
I ran from former merchant Adolphus Nolting’s Rocky Mills plantation, in Hanover County north of Richmond, VA in August 1854. Nolting had bought me and others to labor on his plantation. My wife was at Skinner’s near Norfolk, and I headed back there. My name was RAMSAY. https://t.co/kr1jDdtsKu
On this day in May 1864, I ran from the residence of farmer T. A. Yount near the Catawba railroad station in western North Carolina. I was 17 years old, and might have tried going all the way back home to my family in Columbus, SC, 130 miles to the south. I was called JOHN. https://t.co/ZdtdsrHOGJ
I was jailed in Cumberland Co. NC in April 1856 after being hired out to Dr. Isaac Jackson, of the firm Wortham and Jackson, then processing turpentine in Columbus County. I left and went north, maybe heading back to Warren County when I was captured. My name was WILLIAM. https://t.co/JIuB7A8GqQ
We ran from Johnathan D. Waters’ Arcola plantation in Fort Bend County, TX near Houston on this night in March 1856. We were overworked and were regularly fed only cornmeal mush, and had to leave. We took horses and hoped to make it to Mexico. Our names were JOE and GEORGE. https://t.co/PohnoqvLD9
On the night of August 18, 1854, when I was 14 years old, I left the house of George Ferguson of Wilmington, NC; I had been hired out to him by Alfred L. Price.  Instead of returning to Price as I was supposed to, I hid with friends or family through September. My name was ELLEN. https://t.co/G6sNvh3R6x
In March 1864, despite being heavily pregnant, I managed to flee from farmer Robert Thomas of Gibsonville, NC and escaped to nearby Greensboro. I had been hired to Thomas by Rev. Edward W. Gilliam, an Episcopal minister and son of a wealthy doctor. I was called NANCEY. https://t.co/IkYpggw7GT
I was caught on June 12, 1863 and held in the Wilmington jail, so that Register’s administrator Charles Galloway could retrieve me and hire me out for the benefit of the estate, instead of my own. I was called METHUSELA. https://t.co/ctOoqV81Ks
I didn’t return from an errand on this day in April, 1854, in New Orleans, LA when I was about 7 years old. I must have been returned to Stephen Herriman before his death in June 1854, as I was listed in his estate inventory with my mother and siblings. My name was JIM BROWN. https://t.co/lgsYjmSgPD
I ran from one of William. J. Berry’s plantations on April 4, 1856, possibly Bowieville or Chelsea in Prince George’s County, MD. My free relatives might have found work for me in DC or at a fishery nearby; he was still looking for me at the end of May.  My name was DANIEL. https://t.co/3AX1o9lYgw
I ran from merchant Wesley Clark Troy of Fayetteville, North Carolina, but was caught in Wilmington and held in jail there in June 1864. I might have been hoping to find work in Wilmington, or to travel to the Union lines in New Bern. My name was COLLINS. https://t.co/KFbqFa5OLI
I ran from Harris County, Texas slave trader James D. Cage in early June 1863; I may have had friends to hide me in Houston, or I may have tried to get as far as I could. He was still advertising for me on June 24th. My name was CHARLES. https://t.co/cJl4EperSd
In May 1864, I was caught in Wilmington, NC and held in jail; I claimed to belong to farmer Armistead Burwell of Granville County, 160 miles north. I might have been looking for work when I was taken prisoner. I called myself WILLIAM. https://t.co/Vk4wa4ptuD
In June 1864, I was caught and held in jail in Wilmington, NC; I told them I was running from William Tedder of Darlington, SC, about 150 miles to the west. I may have headed for Wilmington to look for work, or been aiming for the Union line at New Bern. I called myself BOB. https://t.co/Ca8mRqq2mE
I ran from George W. Moore’s farm in New Hanover County, NC in February 1864, and made my way to Wilmington, where my mother Harriet and other relatives lived. I had been hired to Moore by tanner Benjamin Jacobs. He was still looking for me in August 1864. My name was EMMA. https://t.co/KdCT38XTn8
We ran from the Starrville, TX farm of James Spear in 1854, and headed southwest towards Mexico, but we were unable to take enough food with us for our journey. We were caught 260 miles away in Colorado County, TX in mid-March 1854, sick and starving. Our names are UNKNOWN. https://t.co/UrPwMuDv8R
We ran from the Polk County, TX plantation of Otis M. Wheeler in Dec 1855, and were still being hunted in Feb 1856.  I had run about 10 years before and been recaptured. CHARLES had lived in Washington County, TX to the west, and we might have headed there.  I was called CALVIN. https://t.co/2uvDnouju3
I ran from William B. Whitehead’s sugar plantation in  St. Charles Parish, Louisiana about April 1854, and might have headed to New Orleans. Sugar production was brutal work and I wanted to survive, and be free. My name was GEORGE BARRETT. #freedomseekers https://t.co/jtnkD7ybJa
